  "notes": "Scripture records the one roll of Israel's twelve sons in several places: the household register at Bethel (Gen 35:23-26), the names of the children of Israel which came into Egypt, gathered by mother with each son heading his sub-list (Gen 46:8-25), the opening muster of Exodus (Exod 1:2-4), and the chronicler's genealogy (1Chr 2:1-2). The shared core is the same twelve names: Reuben, Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, Zebulun, Joseph, Benjamin, Dan, Naphtali, Gad, and Asher. Each list is grouped a little differently, the sons of the handmaids Bilhah and Zilpah falling in differing order and Joseph and Levi standing in differing places among the lists; these are complementary arrangements of the one family, a matter for further study. Exodus omits Joseph from its count, who was already in Egypt and is told of apart (Exod 1:5-6), so his name is linked only across the three lists that name him. Each son's name is matched to its counterpart by name rather than by position, since the orderings vary.",
